00:45:28.370 --> 00:45:31.560
ALEX BANAYAN: So what's next?

00:45:31.560 --> 00:45:34.500
So I've been working on
this for seven years.

00:45:34.500 --> 00:45:37.866
And seven years went into it.

00:45:37.866 --> 00:45:39.240
And then I'm one
month out of it.

00:45:39.240 --> 00:45:40.198
So it's still very new.

00:45:42.610 --> 00:45:44.620
What I've realized, though, is--

00:45:44.620 --> 00:45:49.020
I heard this story
somewhere in my research.

00:45:49.020 --> 00:45:50.820
I can't even remember
where I read it.

00:45:50.820 --> 00:45:52.670
But it's the story
of a teacher who was

00:45:52.670 --> 00:45:54.910
teaching for Teach for America.

00:45:54.910 --> 00:45:57.000
And she was teaching at
a school in Baltimore.

00:45:57.000 --> 00:45:58.600
It was a really
rough neighborhood

00:45:58.600 --> 00:46:00.420
at a really tough school.

00:46:00.420 --> 00:46:04.600
And she's teaching about I
think a third grade class.

00:46:04.600 --> 00:46:07.715
She realized all right, these
kids need some inspiration.

00:46:07.715 --> 00:46:09.340
So she's like, all
right, today instead

00:46:09.340 --> 00:46:13.170
of doing our math
exercise, I'm going

00:46:13.170 --> 00:46:14.927
to pass out sheets of paper.

00:46:14.927 --> 00:46:17.260
And everyone is going to draw
a picture of the thing you

00:46:17.260 --> 00:46:18.922
want to be when you grow up.

00:46:18.922 --> 00:46:20.150
So she passes out the paper.

00:46:20.150 --> 00:46:21.358
And all the kids are drawing.

00:46:21.358 --> 00:46:23.200
And there was this
one boy sitting

00:46:23.200 --> 00:46:28.996
in the back of the class who
wouldn't pick up a crayon.

00:46:28.996 --> 00:46:30.590
And the teacher was concerned.

00:46:30.590 --> 00:46:32.890
And he had a sad
look on his face.

00:46:32.890 --> 00:46:34.805
But about halfway through
his eyes light up.

00:46:34.805 --> 00:46:36.510
And he starts drawing.

00:46:36.510 --> 00:46:38.210
And at the end of the
class, the teacher

00:46:38.210 --> 00:46:39.230
collects all the papers.

00:46:39.230 --> 00:46:40.349
And the kids go home.

00:46:40.349 --> 00:46:41.390
She's going through them.

00:46:41.390 --> 00:46:46.410
And she sees that kid had drew
a picture of a pizza delivery

00:46:46.410 --> 00:46:48.734
man.

00:46:48.734 --> 00:46:49.650
And she was concerned.

00:46:49.650 --> 00:46:52.190
So she called the
mother that night.

00:46:52.190 --> 00:46:55.820
And the mother said
she wasn't surprised.

00:46:55.820 --> 00:46:58.220
She said that the
only male figure

00:46:58.220 --> 00:47:03.210
in his life who's not
in jail or on drugs

00:47:03.210 --> 00:47:04.820
is his uncle who delivers pizza.

00:47:07.500 --> 00:47:11.600
And what that story taught me
is that young people will always

00:47:11.600 --> 00:47:16.730
reach for the highest
branch they see is possible.

00:47:16.730 --> 00:47:20.720
So it's our job, whether
it's schools or families

00:47:20.720 --> 00:47:25.940
or the media or technology
to illuminate more branches.

00:47:25.940 --> 00:47:28.370
And that's the mission
moving forward.

00:47:28.370 --> 00:47:30.170
As the book evolves--

00:47:30.170 --> 00:47:34.040
